  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Blue Petition for the Birthday Celebration of the Meritorious Official Overseer
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    First Offering: Though unseen to the eye and unheard to the ear, yet in silent mystery the spirits work their transformations. In advance, I contemplate loyalty; in retreat, I ponder service—how could this repay the sovereign's grace? Thus we polish the solemn rites of celestial stars, hoping that the cloud-chariot shall descend.

    Second Offering: The Way's root is one, we are told, transcending all names of sound and scent. When sincere devotion is offered twice, the responsive communion naturally manifests. So we lay these humble tributes before you and dare to wish for lengthened years.

    Third Offering: The stars and heavens abide in stillness, yet all things rise and flourish by their law. Your servant pours out his utmost sincerity in wishing one man's span of days to endure—such earnest prayer shall surely draw down celestial blessings. We your servants are mere ordinary folk, yet fortune has granted us this flourishing age. Our light depends upon sun and moon; we have received unmerited favor and grace. By mountain and river we have sworn our oath, undeserving as we are of renown among the meritorious. Our descendants inherit this blessing, yet all heaven and earth could not repay such kindness. Now that the season of birth returns, we redouble our fervent prayers. We have consulted the sacred registers and solemnly performed this ritual ceremony.

    We humbly beseech: May Your Majesty live as the ancient parasol tree through eight thousand springs—may your line grow ever verdant and flourishing. May you inherit the ninefold blessings of the old sages, and may our realm endure in eternal prosperity.
  footnotes:
    - The 'three offerings' (初獻, 二獻, 三獻) structure the Daoist ritual ceremony (醮) honoring the birthday of a meritorious official.
    - The 'parasol tree of eight thousand springs' (椿樹八千春) alludes to ancient Chinese symbolism for extreme longevity.
    - The 'ninefold blessings' (九五福) derives from the Nine Canons of the Hongfan, representing supreme good fortune in governance.
